TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Critical Theory of Organization Science
AU  - Steffy, Brian D.
AU  - Grimes, Andrew J.
Y1  - 1986/04/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4283115
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4283115
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 322
EP  - 336
VL  - 11
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Critical theory is presented as a general method for analyzing an organization science based on either a natural science or interpretive paradigm. This is accomplished by introducing epistemic inquiry into organization science methodology. Specifically, critical theory provides a means of examining the socio-political interplay among the researcher, the research enterprise, the practitioner, and the organization members. Such an analysis requires the examination of ideology, technology, and praxis.
AB  - Critical theory is presented as a general method for analyzing an organization science based on either a natural science or interpretive paradigm. This is accomplished by introducing epistemic inquiry into organization science methodology. Specifically, critical theory provides a means of examining the socio-political interplay among the researcher, the research enterprise, the practitioner, and the organization members. Such an analysis requires the examination of ideology, technology, and praxis.
